\begin_layout Standard
Physically, the positive-definite problem 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}u=f$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as the displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in response to an applied pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, where the Dirichlet boundary conditions correspond to a material pinned
 at the edges.
 The Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

 is the limit of the displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in response to a force concentrated at a single point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

.
 The Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

 for some example points 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

